'''Elizabeth Larrieu Torres''' (born September 27, 1947) is an American actress, singer, and comedian. Torres is best known for her role as Mahalia Sanchez in the NBC comedy series ''[[The John Larroquette Show]]'' (1993–1996), for which she received two [[Primetime Emmy Award|Primetime Emmy]] and [[Golden Globe Award]]s nominations. She is also known for her role as Patricia "Miss Patty" LaCosta in [[The WB]] family drama series ''[[Gilmore Girls]]'' (2000–07).
==Career== Torres started her career as a comedian and singer working the city's night club circuit with her friend [[Bette Midler]]. In 1971, she was spotted doing one of her acts by the producer of [[Johnny Carson|Johnny Carson's]] ''[[The Tonight Show]]'' who invited her to do a stand-up comedy skit on the show. She made her film debut in 1969 playing a [[prostitute]] in a low-budget movie titled ''Utterly Without Redeeming Social Value''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/80/Liz-Torres.html|title=Liz Torres Biography|accessdate=April 21, 2015}}</ref>
In 1973, Torres played Morticia in ''The Addams Family Fun House'', which was a musical version of the original series. From 1975 to 1976, she was regular cast member on the CBS sitcom, ''[[Phyllis (TV series)|Phyllis]]'', [[Cloris Leachman]]'s spin-off series from ''[[The Mary Tyler Moore Show]]'', succeeding the late [[Barbara Colby]] in the role of Julie Erskine.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0005500/ Liz Torres Actress Credits at IMDb]</ref>
[[File:Cloris Leachman Liz Torres Richard Schaal Phyllis 1975.JPG|thumb|right|200px|(L–R) [[Richard Schaal]], [[Cloris Leachman]] and Liz Torres in ''[[Phyllis (TV series)|Phyllis]]'' (1975)]]
In 1975, she recorded a disco music single called "Hustle Latino" on RCA Records (RCA 10519) arranged, conducted and produced by Michael Zager and appeared on [[Dick Clark]]'s ''[[American Bandstand]]'' to perform the number. In 1976, she played "Cat" in TV's musical special ''[[Pinocchio (1976 TV musical)|Pinocchio]]'' starring [[Sandy Duncan]] In early 1981, she co-starred opposite [[Marla Gibbs]] in ''[[Checking In]]'', a short-lived spin-off of ''[[The Jeffersons]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/liz-torres/190440|title=Liz Torres|website=TVGuide.com}}</ref><ref name="G">{{cite web|url=http://www.gilmoregirls.org/liz.html|title=GilmoreGirls.org : Liz Torres|accessdate=April 21, 2015}}</ref> She had the recurring role on ''[[All in the Family]]'' as Teresa, the boarder at the Bunker house, and guest starred in ''[[Love, American Style]]'', ''[[Hill Street Blues]]'', ''[[L.A. Law]]'', ''[[Knots Landing]]'', ''[[Tracey Takes On...]]'', ''[[Ally McBeal]]'' and ''[[The Nanny]]''.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}
In 1990, Torres was nominated for an [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actress in a Comedy Series]] for her performance on ''[[The Famous Teddy Z]]''. In theater, she has appeared in ''The Ritz'' as Googie Gomez, ''[[Man of La Mancha]]'' as Aldonza, in ''[[House of Blue Leaves]]'' as Bunny, and in ''A Million To Juan'' in 1994 as Mrs. Delgado.<ref name="G"/> After a guest starring appearance as a deceased singer-turned-angel on the [[Donald P. Bellisario]] drama series ''[[Quantum Leap (TV series)|Quantum Leap]]'', Torres had a recurring role on another Bellisario show, ''[[Tequila and Bonetti]]'', as a psychic who hears the dog Tequila's thoughts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/people/liz-torres/|title=Liz Torres|publisher=CBS Interactive|work=TV.com|accessdate=April 21, 2015}}</ref>
From 1993 to 1996, she starred as Mahalia Sanchez in the NBC sitcom ''[[The John Larroquette Show]]''. For her role, she received two [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series]] and [[Golden Globe Award]] nominations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0005500/awards|title=Liz Torres|website=IMDb}}</ref> Torres received two nominations for the [[American Comedy Award]] for the Best Television Performance.<ref name="G"/>
In 1997, Torres co-starred alongside [[Annie Potts]] in the short-lived CBS sitcom, ''[[Over the Top (TV series)|Over the Top]]''. She later co-starred on ''[[First Monday]]'' and ''[[American Family (2002 TV series)|American Family]]''. From 2000 until the series' end in 2007, she was a semi-regular cast member of ''[[Gilmore Girls]]'', on which she played [[Stars Hollow]]'s resident dance teacher, Patty LaCosta.<ref name="G"/> In 2008 she played the role of Juanita in Polish film [[Expecting Love]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.polishfilms.org/film/expecting-love|title=EXPECTING LOVE|website=[[Seattle Polish Film Festival]]|date=April 4, 2008}}</ref>
Torres later guest starred in ''[[Ugly Betty]]'', ''[[Desperate Housewives]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://crushable.com/entertainment/liz-torres-to-guest-on-desperate-housewives/|title=Liz Torres to Guest on "Desperate Housewives"|work=Crushable|accessdate=April 21, 2015}}</ref> ''[[Private Practice (TV series)|Private Practice]]'', ''[[Scandal (TV series)|Scandal]]'' and ''[[Devious Maids]]''.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}
==Personal life== Torres was born in the [[Bronx]] borough of [[New York City]], where her parents had settled after moving from [[Puerto Rico]]. There she received her primary and secondary education.
Torres resides in [[Los Angeles]], where she is a member of the board of directors of Write Act Repertory. She is married to the movie producer and founder of [[The Kushner-Locke Company]], [[Peter Locke (producer)|Pete Locke]].<ref name="G"/>
